<p style="text-align:justify;">Island is low and sandy but covered with herbage; on it and on adjoining hill the Indians have their Huts.  The Bay is directly opposite where they put out their nets, and go &#8211; a spearing every calm night with flambeaux.  They take as fine Trout and Whitefish as are found in any part of the Lake.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">From Grand Island bay the distance to Lake Michigan cannot be more than 60 or 70 miles, as the Indians sleep but one night on the road when they rise expedition, which proves that the two Lakes run for a certain distance nearly parallel and approximate much more than they are made to do in any of the Maps we have yet had of this Country.</p>
